INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'f78582df-a533-4981-b5e1-825814402536',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Tailwind CSS Design Tokens — Encode Your System in tailwind.config, Not in Class Names$escape$,
  $escape$Magic numbers in class names (`text-[14px]`, `mt-[22px]`) are a design system smell. Tailwind's `theme` block in `tailwind.config.ts` is your single source of truth — define tokens once, reference them everywhere via generated utilities.

Extend `theme.extend.colors` with semantic names (`brand`, `surface`, `on-surface`) rather than raw hues. Use CSS custom properties as token values so runtime theming stays possible without purge issues — Tailwind resolves the variable at build time for IntelliSense but the browser resolves the value at runtime.

For spacing, add a custom scale under `theme.extend.spacing` (`sidebar: '280px'`, `header: '56px'`) so layout constants live in config, not scattered across components. Typography tokens go in `theme.extend.fontSize` as `[size, { lineHeight, letterSpacing, fontWeight }]` tuples — one token carries the full text style.

With `@layer base` you can wire CSS variables to Tailwind tokens cleanly, letting you swap entire palettes by changing `:root` values. Arbitrary values should be a last resort, never the default.$escape$,
  $escape$// tailwind.config.ts
import type { Config } from 'tailwindcss'

export default {
  theme: {
    extend: {
      colors: {
        brand: 'var(--color-brand)',
        surface: 'var(--color-surface)',
        'on-surface': 'var(--color-on-surface)',
      },
      spacing: {
        sidebar: '280px',
        header: '56px',
      },
      fontSize: {
        'label-sm': ['0.75rem', { lineHeight: '1rem', fontWeight: '500' }],
        'body-md': ['0.875rem', { lineHeight: '1.5rem', fontWeight: '400' }],
      },
    },
  },
} satisfies Config$escape$,
