INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '297df4c2-1231-40b1-a859-46fe8ace4eea',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Tailwind CSS Animations — GPU-Composited Properties and prefers-reduced-motion$escape$,
  $escape$Tailwind's `transition-all` class transitions every CSS property, including layout-affecting ones like `width`, `height`, and `padding`. That forces the browser through layout and paint on every frame — a silent performance killer on mobile.

Restrict yourself to `transition-transform` and `transition-opacity`. Both run entirely on the compositor thread, skipping layout and paint. Combine them with `duration-{n}` and `ease-{in|out|in-out}` utilities for full control without touching the main thread.

Tailwind ships the `motion-reduce:` variant out of the box — it compiles directly to `@media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce)`. Apply it to strip or neutralize motion for users who've opted out. This is an accessibility requirement, not optional polish.

For keyframe utilities: `animate-pulse` and `animate-ping` are compositor-safe — they use `opacity` and `transform` internally. `animate-bounce` is technically transform-based too, but its easing curve can feel jarring; prefer `animate-pulse` for loading states.

Skip `will-change-transform` unless a profiler confirms a real gain. It promotes elements to isolated GPU layers, consuming memory proportional to element size — it can hurt more than it helps if applied broadly.$escape$,
  $escape$<button
  class="
    transition-transform duration-200 ease-out
    hover:-translate-y-1 active:translate-y-0
    focus-visible:ring-2 focus-visible:ring-offset-2 focus-visible:outline-none
    motion-reduce:transition-none motion-reduce:hover:translate-y-0
  "
>
  Submit
</button>

<!-- Loading skeleton: compositor-safe pulse, silenced for reduced-motion -->
<div class="animate-pulse motion-reduce:animate-none">
  <div class="h-4 w-48 rounded bg-zinc-200" />
</div>$escape$,
  $escape$javascript$escape$,
