INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'e0832b13-a818-4341-a5ea-bf9ecd3f4a96',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$tailwindcss @apply Pitfalls — and When to Extract a Component Instead$escape$,
  $escape$Reaching for @apply the moment a class string gets long is a common mistake. First problem: arbitrary values don't work inside @apply — `@apply text-[14px]` throws a build error because arbitrary values are resolved at the utility layer, not the component layer. Second problem: @apply pulls utilities into your CSS as static rules, bypassing JIT tree-shaking and bloating output when the class is used sparingly.

If a value recurs across the codebase, add it to `theme.extend` in `tailwind.config.ts` instead — `text-brand-sm` becomes a real design token: autocompleted, purgeable, and documented. If the styling is tied to a markup structure (icon + label, card with hover ring), extract a JSX or Vue component — co-locating markup and utilities is the entire point of utility-first CSS.

Reserve @apply strictly for global, markup-agnostic patterns: prose resets, third-party widget overrides, or base-layer typography defaults. In every other case you're working against Tailwind's model, not with it.$escape$,
  $escape$// tailwind.config.ts — extend the theme instead of hiding values in @apply
export default {
  theme: {
    extend: {
      fontSize: { 'brand-sm': ['0.8125rem', { lineHeight: '1.25rem' }] },
      colors: { brand: { subtle: '#F0F4FF', DEFAULT: '#4F6EF7' } },
    },
  },
};

// ❌ Breaks at build time — arbitrary values illegal inside @apply
// .btn { @apply text-[13px] px-[18px] rounded-[6px]; }

// ✅ Extract a component when markup and styles travel together
// <Button className="text-brand-sm bg-brand px-4 py-2 rounded-md" />$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
